briefdescription.para: Maximum length of a string variable.

detaileddescription.para: This defines the maximum number of characters allowed for string variables in the program.

briefdescription.para: Maximum stack depth for GOSUB, PROC, and FN calls.

detaileddescription.para: This defines the maximum depth of nesting for procedure (PROC), function (FN), and GOSUB calls in the program. This stack depth is used to track the return addresses for each call level.

briefdescription.para: Maximum stack depth for FOR...NEXT loops.

detaileddescription.para: This defines the maximum depth of nesting for FOR...NEXT loops in the program. It controls how many loops can be nested before the stack is considered full.

briefdescription.para: Special line number where EVAL code is inserted dynamically.

detaileddescription.para: This constant represents the line number where the code inserted by an EVAL statement will be placed. It is used to handle dynamic program changes during execution.

briefdescription.para: RETURN statement line after EVAL code.

detaileddescription.para: This line is used as the destination after the dynamically inserted EVAL code completes. The program will return to this line number after executing the EVAL block.

briefdescription.para: Macro to convert a token into a string representation.

detaileddescription.para: This macro is used to turn a preprocessor token into a string.

briefdescription.para: Helper macro to stringify a token.

detaileddescription.para: This macro expands the AUX macro to convert an expression into a string.
This flag indicates that the program is paused at a breakpoint for debugging.
This flag indicates that the program is in step-by-step debugging mode.
This flag indicates that the program is running in trace mode, where each instruction is logged.
This defines the maximum number of sprites that can be used in the program. A sprite represents a graphical object that can be displayed and manipulated.

memberdef.name: PARAMS_START
memberdef.initializer: [[maybe_unused]] int itemtype = BIP_INT; \ [[maybe_unused]] int64_t intval = 0; \ [[maybe_unused]] double doubleval = 0; \ [[maybe_unused]] char* strval = NULL; \ [[maybe_unused]] char oldval = 0; \ [[maybe_unused]] char oldct = 0; \ [[maybe_unused]] char* oldptr = 0; \ [[maybe_unused]] char const* oldnextptr = NULL; \ [[maybe_unused]] int gotone = 0; \ [[maybe_unused]] int bracket_depth = 0; \ [[maybe_unused]] char const* item_begin = ctx->ptr;

detaileddescription.para: This macro is used to initialize the context for parsing the parameters of a function or procedure. It sets up necessary local variables like bracket depth, parameter pointer, and the item start pointer.

briefdescription.para: Get a function parameter of a specific type.

detaileddescription.para: This macro is used to retrieve a function parameter of a specific type (string, double, integer) from the input context, ensuring that the parsing is done correctly, respecting the parameter's type. It processes the tokens, sets the corresponding parameter variable, and moves the context pointers.

parameterdescription.para: The type of the parameter to get (string, double, integer, or variable).

memberdef.name: PARAMS_END

detaileddescription.para: This macro is used to check if all function parameters have been parsed correctly. It verifies that the closing bracket ) is encountered and throws an error if there are parameters remaining to be processed.

parameterdescription.para: The name of the function or procedure being processed.
The value to return in case of error.

memberdef.name: PARAMS_END_VOID

briefdescription.para: End fetching function parameters for void return functions.

detaileddescription.para: Similar to PARAMS_END but used for functions that do not return a value. It ensures that the function's parameter list is terminated properly.

parameterdescription.para: The name of the function or procedure being processed.

briefdescription.para: Simplified version of accept() for quick handling of token acceptance.

detaileddescription.para: This macro tries to accept a specific token in the context. If the token does not match, it immediately returns from the current function, providing an efficient exit mechanism for expected token checks.
